## Task

Extract label and settings from export data using typed property reading.

## Critical Fix vs JS Scanner

The JS scanner uses a 25-byte stride assumption:
```
FString(key) + 25 bytes metadata + FString(value)
```

This is WRONG. UE uses tagged serialization:
```
FName(PropertyName) + FName(PropertyType) + i32(size) + [type data] + [value bytes]
```

The 25-byte gap coincidentally works on test files because they only have simple
scalar properties. It will break on:
- EnumProperty (extra type name)
- StructProperty (nested structure)
- ArrayProperty (variable length)
- Asset references

## Implementation (using unreal_asset)

```rust
use unreal_asset::{Asset, exports::Export, properties};
use indexmap::IndexMap;

pub fn extract_properties(asset: &Asset<File>) -> (Option<String>, IndexMap<String, String>) {
    let mut label = None;
    let mut settings = IndexMap::new();

    for export in &asset.asset_data.exports {
        let Some(normal) = export.get_normal_export() else { continue };

        for prop in &normal.properties {
            let key = prop.get_name().get_owned_content();
            let value_str = property_to_string(prop);

            if let Some(val) = value_str {
                // Capture label
                if key == "ActorLabel" || key == "LabelOverride" {
                    label = Some(val.clone());
                }

                // First value wins (avoid duplicates)
                if !settings.contains_key(&key) {
                    settings.insert(key, val);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    (label, settings)
}

fn property_to_string(prop: &PropertyData) -> Option<String> {
    match prop {
        PropertyData::StrPropertyData(s) => s.value.as_ref().map(|v| v.to_string()),
        PropertyData::FloatPropertyData(f) => Some(format!("{:.6}", f.value)),
        PropertyData::DoublePropertyData(d) => Some(format!("{:.6}", d.value)),
        PropertyData::BoolPropertyData(b) => Some(b.value.to_string()),
        PropertyData::EnumPropertyData(e) => Some(e.value.get_owned_content()),
        PropertyData::StructPropertyData(s) => Some(format_struct(s)),
        PropertyData::NamePropertyData(n) => Some(n.value.get_owned_content()),
        PropertyData::IntPropertyData(i) => Some(i.value.to_string()),
        PropertyData::BytePropertyData(b) => Some(b.value.to_string()),
        _ => None, // Skip complex types for now
    }
}
